snippet.textDisplay:
Yeah that Apple scanning your phone thing is not a good thing, in any way. If it can be used to detect child porn, it can and will be used to detect "thought crimes".
China? It'll be used to detect and jail anti-government images. Russia? It will be used to detect and jail gay and trans people.
Middle-east? It will be used to detect and harass Christians. USA? It will be used to detect and harass people with a less than favorable opinion of the police.

Now you know why privacy organizations are so up in arms about this. A backdoor is a backdoor, regardless if it's "for the children".
The fact that apple is trying to spin this as a pro-privacy thing is just... disgusting beyond words.

snippet.textDisplay: You neglected to mention the insanely high potential for false positive matches given Apple's intent of implementing perceptual hashes, which will necessitate otherwise baseless human review of iPhones where suspect material has been "found". At no stage in the process will the user be informed that this is taking place, by the way. So you can look forward to the Apple outsourcing partner's breakroom featuring print outs of your naked wife. And on the off chance that your own lawfully taken adult pics trigger the system AND get marked by human review as offensive, you're going to have a hard time proving to the authorities that you're innocent because suddenly it's a "proven fact" that CSAM was found on your phone. On top of that, malicious actors could send known CSAM material to, say, dissidents in an email which would 100% trigger the whole process. There is an endless list of horror scenarios being enabled by this, including widening the net beyond CSAM inevitably.
